The whole multitude took up the cry, and he was unarrimously elected. lt was in vain that he protested that he was only a catechumen and a laic; his entreaties aud remon- strances only made them redouble their sager demand. He went into the hall of justice and affected to con- demn certain criminals to severe turture, but the people were not to be deceived. A guard was set to watch him, yet he made his escape again, and was again discovered.
